---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="About" description="About this Peru earth science project and its creator.">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-700 to-red-900 text-white py-20 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <p class="text-red-300 uppercase tracking-widest text-sm mb-2">About This Project</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">My Connection to Peru</h1>
      <p class="text-red-100 text-lg">A personal, academic, and spiritual exploration of the land I call home.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-16 space-y-12">

    <!-- Personal ties -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-stone-100 p-8">
      <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">My Ties to Peru</h2>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            I was born and raised in Peru — it is my home country, the place that shaped who I am. Growing up, I experienced firsthand the breathtaking contrasts of Peruvian geography: the dry coastal city, the towering Andes visible on clear days, and the stories of jungle regions that felt like another world entirely.
          </p>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            My family is Peruvian, and though I now study at Ensign College in Salt Lake City, Utah, Peru remains deeply embedded in my identity. The food, the culture, the language, and the landscapes are all part of how I see the world.
          </p>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
            Studying the earth science of Peru is not just an academic exercise for me — it is a way of understanding the physical forces that created the land where my family lives and where I grew up. Every earthquake, every river, every mountain range is personal.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Interesting physical geography fact -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-stone-100 p-8">
      <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">One Fascinating Physical Geography Fact</h2>
          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-400 rounded-r-xl p-4 mb-4">
            <p class="text-amber-800 font-semibold text-lg">Peru contains all 32 of the world's climate zones.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            According to the World Meteorological Organization, there are 32 recognized climate types on Earth — and Peru is one of the only countries in the world that contains all of them within its borders. This extraordinary fact is possible because of the interaction between:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-stone-600 space-y-1 mb-3 ml-2">
            <li>The <strong>Andes Mountains</strong>, which create dramatic altitude gradients (sea level to 6,768 m)</li>
            <li>The <strong>Humboldt Current</strong>, a cold ocean current that creates coastal desert conditions</li>
            <li>The <strong>Amazon Basin</strong>, which generates its own humid tropical climate system</li>
            <li>Peru's <strong>tropical latitude</strong>, which intensifies solar radiation and moisture</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
            No other country of similar size has this level of climatic variety. It is one reason Peru is considered one of the world's <em>megadiverse</em> nations — the variety of climates directly drives the variety of ecosystems and species.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Spiritual reflection -->
    <section class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-stone-100 p-8">
      <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-4">The Earth as a Witness of God</h2>

          <!-- Scripture quote -->
          <blockquote class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 rounded-r-xl p-5 mb-6 italic text-stone-700">
            <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
              "All things denote there is a God; yea, even the earth, and all things that are upon the face of it, yea, and its motion, yea, and also all the planets which move in their regular form do witness that there is a Supreme Creator."
            </p>
            <footer class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-blue-700 not-italic">— Alma 30:44, Book of Mormon</footer>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">
            When I study Peru's earth processes, I see this scripture come alive. The physical world of Peru — its mountains, rivers, earthquakes, and ecosystems — bears a profound testimony of intelligent design and divine creation.
          </p>

          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
            <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4">
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-1">The Andes</h4>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm">The Andes are the longest continental mountain range on Earth — 7,000 km stretching across South America. Their formation through tectonic plate subduction follows precise physical laws. The order and scale of this process speaks of a Creator who engineers with intention, not randomness.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4">
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-1">The Humboldt Current</h4>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm">This cold ocean current brings nutrient-rich water to Peru's coast, supporting one of the world's most productive marine ecosystems. The interconnection between ocean temperature, wind patterns, and marine life reveals a system too finely balanced to be accidental.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4">
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-1">Amazon Biodiversity</h4>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm">Peru's Amazon region contains an estimated 50,000 plant species and thousands of unique animal species. The complexity and beauty of life that has adapted to every ecological niche speaks to the creative power of a God who delights in variety and life.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-xl p-4">
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-1">Tectonic Stability in Motion</h4>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm">Peru sits on the Nazca Plate — a region of constant tectonic activity. Yet Earth's crust, though in motion, follows consistent and predictable laws of physics. This regularity allows civilization to exist. The very order within the earth's motion testifies of divine governance.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
            To study earth science is to read one of God's oldest texts. Every stratum of rock, every river carving a canyon, every seed germinating in Andean soil is a page in that book. Peru — with its extraordinary diversity of natural processes — offers an unusually rich testimony that the earth was designed with purpose, beauty, and care.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</Layout>
